Billionaire and legendary investor David Booth: Here's how to invest smartly right now so you come out of the pandemic with financial security ...  investment principles do what they were designed to do: Help meet your financial goals. 1. Develop a long-term strategy you can stick with I've experienced a lot of market tumult during my 50-year career in finance. The most important advice I can give is to stay invested and to try not to time the markets. There's no compelling evidence that trying to time the market's ups and downs is a winning strategy. Timing markets can be costly because there is no "catch up" or "do over." Think of all the people that sold equities as stocks fell in 2008, only to miss the rally in 2009 or the subsequent 11-year bull run. Instead, you need to identify your goals and work backward to develop a plan you can stick with over time, regardless ...

Many Arizona children missing shots, doctor visits amid COVID-19 pandemic ... Without change, pediatricians fear we could face a second wave of sickness in the fall and winter — this time with illnesses like measles and whooping cough. You can chalk it up to parents avoiding the doctor's office and ER for fear of exposing their children to COVID-19. Because of these missed visits, doctors are also seeing more asthma, diabetes, and other chronic illness flare-ups. In Pima County, health experts are reminding parents time is of the essence. It's important to get back on track because many shots need more than one dose to be effective. This is especially important for those back-to-school shots. March (Image: GETTY/BBC) Yet despite hairdressers remaining closed, the Queen's hair has been in perfect condition each and every time she has been seen since lockdown began. According to sources, the Queen has been looking after her own hair while isolating at Windsor Castle. A royal source told the Sun on Sunday, the Queen's signature barnet look has been maintained as a result of the Queen undertaking touch-ups. The source told the Sun on Sunday: "The Queen has done her own hair for years at Balmoral during her summer holidays and so she's used to it.
